<div id="review_770482619" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/770482619" />
    <a title="Joe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25882000-joe"><img alt="Joe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1436707093p2/25882000.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/770482619?book_show_action=true">Nov 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe" href="/user/show/25882000-joe">Joe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/25882000-joe?shelf=mystery-thriller">mystery-thriller</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/25882000-joe?shelf=reread">reread</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer770482619" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15668460003917659603">The Deep Blue Good-By introduces Travis McGee, a “salvage consultant” based out of his houseboat, The Busted Flush - which he won in a poker game - in Ft. Lauderdale. (The Florida “landscape” in this series as close as something inanimate can come to being a character.) McGee “helps” people find what they’ve “lost” – usually just outside the boundaries of the law – and then splits the proceeds with his clients. <br/><br/>Travis is a big handsome lug, who likes the ladies – and they him; his cocktails, par</span>
  <span id="freeText15668460003917659603" style="display:none">The Deep Blue Good-By introduces Travis McGee, a “salvage consultant” based out of his houseboat, The Busted Flush - which he won in a poker game - in Ft. Lauderdale. (The Florida “landscape” in this series as close as something inanimate can come to being a character.) McGee “helps” people find what they’ve “lost” – usually just outside the boundaries of the law – and then splits the proceeds with his clients. <br /><br />Travis is a big handsome lug, who likes the ladies – and they him; his cocktails, particularly Boodles gin – although always in moderation; and his bachelor independence. We meet Travis as a fully developed character, a crusading outsider and self-described “knight in rusty armor”. He narrates his adventures and pontificates often – usually on women and the “declining” state of the world - and we pick up bits and pieces of his obscure history as the series progresses.<br /><br />The books follow – from the start – this formula. Through word of mouth, i.e. a friend of a friend, Travis is approached and hired – often by a damsel in distress – to find and/or return something valuable. McGee, usually with some reluctance and contingent on his current bank account balance, picks up the case and with some help from his connections, does some sleuthing – and occasionally traveling – until he zeroes in on what is always a very “bad guy” or some “bad people”. This is the hook for both Travis and the reader as now the hunt becomes “personal” – a contest between good and evil. <br /><br />Travis usually gets into some serious trouble near the conclusion – but always saves the day. Surprisingly – or maybe not – this formula worked for 21 books – starting with this one. (Current day authors – Carl Hiaasen, Stephen King and Robert Parker – even Kurt Vonnegut - just to name a few – love(d) this guy.)<br /><br />It has been a while – years in fact – since I’ve read a Travis McGee adventure. I probably read this one in high school. Although dated and at times a tad ponderous, i.e. Travis’ observations/pontifications – The Blue Good-By is still a fun read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15668460003917659603" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


