    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_311253566" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/311253566" />
    <a title="Jacqie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2133111-jacqie"><img alt="Jacqie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1394055507p2/2133111.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/311253566?book_show_action=true">Apr 12, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jacqie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jacqie" href="/user/show/2133111-jacqie">Jacqie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780752847672" href="/book/show/570650.The_Deep_Blue_Goodbye">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer311253566" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3181063981350937364">The writing is actually a 3 or a 4, but the attitudes toward women in this book are extremely condescending in a subversive way, and brought the rating down.<br/><br/>MacDonald can write a potboiler mystery. He&apos;s got fist fights, boats, cars, and shady characters. And women, but I&apos;ll get to them. A &quot;fixer&quot; main character who will get what you want as long as he gets half. A main character given to superior, worldly musings on the sad state of the world, that make you feel superior and worldly as you read </span>
  <span id="freeText3181063981350937364" style="display:none">The writing is actually a 3 or a 4, but the attitudes toward women in this book are extremely condescending in a subversive way, and brought the rating down.<br /><br />MacDonald can write a potboiler mystery. He's got fist fights, boats, cars, and shady characters. And women, but I'll get to them. A "fixer" main character who will get what you want as long as he gets half. A main character given to superior, worldly musings on the sad state of the world, that make you feel superior and worldly as you read those musings. He's entertaining.<br /><br />I don't know if I'd call it a mystery. There's a mysterious treasure to be found, but it's found by deceit and torture, not by any real detective work other than to find the right guy to torture information from. The detective techniques are so obsolete at this time that it's like reading about another planet- that's kind of interesting.<br /><br />And then there's the women. In the first 30 pages, you meet 3. Our fearless hero McGee sleeps with one and has the chance to sleep with another. The third he sleeps with before the book is over. He's propositioned by several other women throughout the course if the book, but I think he only sleeps with one more- the heroine. I could be wrong, though. The sexual politics of the 60's, seen through the eyes of McGee, are a fascinating anthropological study. Again, it's like visiting another planet. <br /><br />There seem to be two types of women: ladies and "coarse" women. Each female character in the book is described in excruciating physical detail, so you know right away who has "delicate features" and who is "raddled" and usually overweight. Ladies can be hysterical, delicate, childish, and submissive. And that's just fine. Raddled types are more forthright, don't care who they sleep with, have no self awareness, and are from a lower social class. Blood will tell, apparently. McGee's friend Chookie and Cathy, the woman who gets him involved in the case, sort of straddle the line, so to speak. They are dancers, obviously lower class, but McGee likes them well enough not to screw them for no reason at all. Although he'll screw them he thinks there's a decent reason. They have either spunk or strength. <br /><br />Lois, the love interest of the book, is just bizarre. I cannot picture a real woman acting anything like her. SPOILERS FOLLOW:<br /><br />Lois is victimized by the villain of the book. Apparently he likes breaking ladies' spirit. The thing is, even after he puts hands on her against her will and then leaves for a while, she decides to give him another chance and gets onto his boat alone with him,to be nice, knowing that he doesn't respect any boundaries. You can't say she was asking for it, but she certainly made one of the stupidest decisions I've ever seen. Then she's "hysterical", that lovely term for women who have PTSD. I know the plot demands it, but a doctor comes to treat her and then decides that the best thing for her is to stay in her house alone with a total stranger of a man(McGee) to take care of her. How is that in any way a remotely responsible decision on the part of a physician? Did they commonly leave traumatized women with strange men as nurses in the 60's? Then we get a very parent/child relationship between Lois and McGee- quite disturbing, really. It reminds me a lot of Robert Heinlein's writing on women. Maybe it was progressive at the time (in itself a frightening thought) but it comes across now as paternalistic and condescending. Travis decides whether Lois needs kindness or cruelty, depending on if he thinks she's wallowing in an emotional state or being a good girl. Chilling. Although I kind of wanted to slap Lois myself during some passages- she's really annoying for a paragon.<br /><br />Anyway, Lois is gone by the end of the book and it's really all McGee's fault. His hubris led to disaster. I don't know if that was the point of the book or not.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3181063981350937364" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


