<div id="review_1319140339" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1319140339" />
    <a title="Steve" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1254714-steve"><img alt="Steve" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513279210p2/1254714.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1319140339?book_show_action=true">Jun 27, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve" href="/user/show/1254714-steve">Steve</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/3049647-the-deep-blue-good-by">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1254714-steve?shelf=crime-badness-noir">crime-badness-noir</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1319140339" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10454398653621677467">Ooops. Forgot to write a review. Very good opening for the Travis McGee series. I found myself liking Trav a lot better on the ground floor. Little things that have annoyed in the three or four books that I have read out of sequence, such as McGee&apos;s fixation on himself and how he looks, his way with various disposable &quot;bunnies,&quot; and his constant philosophizing, seemed softer, not as packaged. He has his flaws, and he seems aware of them. But he&apos;s a good guy. Maybe he won me over as he looked out</span>
  <span id="freeText10454398653621677467" style="display:none">Ooops. Forgot to write a review. Very good opening for the Travis McGee series. I found myself liking Trav a lot better on the ground floor. Little things that have annoyed in the three or four books that I have read out of sequence, such as McGee's fixation on himself and how he looks, his way with various disposable "bunnies," and his constant philosophizing, seemed softer, not as packaged. He has his flaws, and he seems aware of them. But he's a good guy. Maybe he won me over as he looked out an airplane window, musing over the open spaces, and how the "180 million" haven't yet discovered those spaces. Dude. We're over 300 million in my lifetime, and our border is a "Come On In" welcome sign. <br /><br />OK. Enough of that. As some have pointed out, some of the women often come across as flat characters. But only some. The ones the count, victims of the villain Junior Allen, are very real and very damaged. Allen is a bad man, and a real risk of making this a one book standalone. There are mechanical characters and mechanical scenes that seem to dominate the first third of the book. (It was getting close to Meh.) But once McGee started to investigating the background of some soldiers, and the jewels they brought back from the war, things really kick in. Set in the early 60s Florida beach scene, this book is a fascinating cultural time capsule. Clearly MacDonald was no fan of the younger generation. It's not so much judgmental as it is a perceptive awareness that a cultural shift is occurring, and that concepts such as honor and duty and truthfulness, are just not now valued or even understood by some. And then there is Junior Allen. MacDonald can do Evil with the best of them. And the way he MacDonald rolls him out, by keeping him at periphery of the novel, is masterful. When he finally shows up, the Dread is firmly in place. In the end, this is an achingly sad book, and one that establishes some lasting psychological (and physical) scar tissue on Travis McGee. He made some mistakes, people suffered, and MacDonald, in his authorial wisdom, didn't try to paper those mistakes over. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10454398653621677467" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


