  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2031977494" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2031977494" />
    <a title="Dave" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35045983-dave"><img alt="Dave" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1496413985p2/35045983.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2031977494?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dave" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dave" href="/user/show/35045983-dave">Dave</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780449033005" href="/book/show/761823.The_Deep_Blue_Good_By">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35045983-dave?shelf=read-borrowed">read-borrowed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35045983-dave?shelf=travis-mcgee-series">travis-mcgee-series</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2031977494" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2789367919759818073">“Deep Blue Good-By” (1964) is the first novel in the 21-gun series of Travis McGee novels by John D. McDonald. It is one of the best of the entire series. McGee is a beach bum who lives on a houseboat (“The Busted Flush” – named after the poker game in which he won the boat) in Ft. Lauderdale and eschews nine-to-five jobs, payroll taxes, and Madison Avenue. He makes his living doing “salvage work,” that is, he goes out and gets things have been taken from people and takes a fifty percent cut of </span>
  <span id="freeText2789367919759818073" style="display:none">“Deep Blue Good-By” (1964) is the first novel in the 21-gun series of Travis McGee novels by John D. McDonald. It is one of the best of the entire series. McGee is a beach bum who lives on a houseboat (“The Busted Flush” – named after the poker game in which he won the boat) in Ft. Lauderdale and eschews nine-to-five jobs, payroll taxes, and Madison Avenue. He makes his living doing “salvage work,” that is, he goes out and gets things have been taken from people and takes a fifty percent cut of what is salvaged. His world is filled with boats and bikinis and booze. His friend, Tiger, is just down the marina on a houseboat where there is a never-ending party.<br /><br />The key to this book is the narration by the McGee character who has a never-ending supply of thoughts and concerns about things going on in the American scene, including how many people are stuck in nine- to-five lives with dead-end, boring, meaningless jobs and views on the drug war (particularly marijuana). He is a rough-and-tumble character with a heart of gold. Besides the legendary houseboat, he drives a car that is a Rolls Royce front with the rear converted to a pickup truck and painted a ghastly blue.<br /><br />In this novel, McGee decides to tangle with Junior Allen, a burly conman who is like a shark in the water circling the weakest prey and picking them up and slowly, methodically, chewing them apart, bit by bit. Allen specializes in taking advantage of weak, needy women and, not only uses them, but rips their heart and souls out until there is nothing left of them but a barely-functioning heap of flesh. One of them, Cathy Kerr, comes to McGee’s attention after Junior not only made a fool of her and walked out on her, but also stole a fortune that her father had buried somewhere – a fortune her father had somehow taken home after serving in World War II in India and China and other parts. Another, who started out as a proper lady before Junior got to her, was left as a barely-alive alcoholic shut-in who hadn’t eaten in weeks. McGee plays nursemaid, bringing her back to health, and then goes after the villain. And then there is a young innocent who Junior is out to break apart. She has no idea how nasty and vile a creature Junior really is or what real evil is out there.<br /><br />The book flows smoothly and the characterizations that MacDonald creates are first-class from businessmen in the Great Plains to a soap- opera family on a Texas ranch to the twenty-year olds who are so cold, empty, and used-up that there is nothing bright and alive left in them, just bitter games. The book is not just talk, though, as there are great fight scenes as McGee and Junior duke it out time after time.<br />Although McGee essentially does detective <br />work in finding out what Junior stole and plotting some way to get the goods back from Junior, he is not a detective. What makes this book groove along is the way McGee angles and works to get justice for those who Junior wronged (and hopefully a few dollars too).</span>
  <a data-text-id="2789367919759818073" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

